"Price’s last active audit session closed at 17:58:09 the previous day.\n\nHis classified credential authority was suspended at 18:03:42.\n\nHis extension was disabled at 18:04:01.\n\nThe later office request had been created at 06:41:18 that morning.\n\nGrant displayed only the fields required for the comparison. Price saw his name, his office, and DIA-SAR-PRICE-01 attached to a record class he had never used.\n\nNSB-EMERGENCY CONTINUITY REQUEST.\n\nHe stared at it long enough for Shah to touch the edge of his sleeve.\n\n“Did you create that record?” Grant asked.\n\n“No.”\n\n“Did you assign SSO-NS-004?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Did your original request name WSS-4, Hartwell, K-17, Phase B, or source reconstruction?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Did you ask another person or automated service to add those fields after your access ended?”\n\n“No.”\n\nShah stopped the questioning there. Price had authenticated what he had done and denied a defined set of acts. He had not waived unrelated personnel issues, speculated about a constructor, or accepted anyone else’s theory.\n\nGrant asked whether he would sign a voluntary statement attaching the complete original request and the suspension chronology, including his expedited-retention flag and rejected access attempt.\n\nPrice understood the choice. If he refused, the later record would continue using his name while the only authenticated version of his conduct remained inside a personnel system built to judge him. If he agreed, he preserved the limit that separated his request from the operational route—and gave DIA a clean record of the rule he had knowingly pressed.\n\nHe looked at the camera rather than Grant.\n\n“Include the rejected access attempt.”\n\nShah turned toward him. “Leland.”\n\n“They’ll use it whether I include it or not.” His mouth had gone dry. “I want the sequence complete.”\n\nAt 11:48:26, Price authenticated the bounded statement with a new voluntary review-session receipt. He did not ask to speak to Julie O’Donnell. He did not thank her. He did not offer to help.\n\nHe placed his real request where the borrowed one could no longer replace it.\n\nSecure MPD Evidence Intake\nWashington, D.C.\n11:51 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nGrant returned Price’s statement through the DCIS source channel, not through the office production. The DIA originals remained at DIA. The office original remained under Sterling-office custody. Grant created a derivative set that preserved the two sources as separate components, with separate custodians, clock bases, produced fields, withheld fields, integrity statements, and proof ceilings.\n\nThe comparison began with time because time required the least interpretation.\n\nPrice’s active authority ended more than twelve hours before SO-NS-REQ-6540 was created. The DIA repository showed the authenticated act that created his original request. The administrative-review ledger showed the end of the credential and session authority capable of creating another DIA submission. Neither record claimed authority over the office workflow.\n\nThe office produced the complete event classes its system generated for a direct external requestor, an inherited request, and an internal continuity construction between 05:45 and 07:00. It certified that the range was complete for those classes, while withholding protected narrative and unrelated communications.\n\nGrant aligned the categories without forcing the clocks into one invented time source.\n\nPrice’s original supplied his authenticated request and repository receipt.\n\nThe access-review original supplied the end of his active authority.\n\nThe office original supplied the later construction and the fields it had inherited or added.\n\nThe first match was exact: `DIA-SAR-PRICE-01`.\n\nThe second was Price’s identity string.\n\nThe office event range showed how the identity had traveled. A source-inheritance service imported Price’s request reference and normalized the requestor field into the office workflow. Forty-three seconds later, a continuity-construction process created the operational branch. The produced record showed the order of those system events and the service categories that owned them. It did not expose the account, certificate, person, or internal instruction that had caused the construction process to run.\n\nA direct Price submission would have required one of two paths defined by the office custodian: an external credential challenge tied to an active source-agency session, or an office witness release documenting that a source instruction had been received through another authorized channel. The complete event-class production contained neither. The inheritance path had supplied enough identity for the office system to name Price without supplying the act that would make the later instruction his.\n\nGrant placed the office transformation beside the DIA original without combining them. The inherited fields aligned at the request reference and identity. The authored fields diverged at the mission.\n\nThe differences were larger.\n\nDIA-SAR-PRICE-01 requested preservation and read-only source review. SO-NS-REQ-6540 converted that reference into an `NSB-EMERGENCY` continuity path. It added the signer asset, WSS-4, Hartwell, K17-PHASE-B, and the source-reconstruction category. The office transformation field identified those entries as continuity-routing additions, not terms present in Price’s original.\n\nHackett read the list and said, “Someone expanded his request.”\n\n“Someone or a service,” Grant said. “The record does not identify the constructor yet.”\n\nOffice counsel seized the distinction. “Continuity systems lawfully inherit source identity and request references. A later route can derive from an earlier need without the original requester entering every operational field.”\n\nJulie looked at the derivative on the fixed display. “Then who submitted the derived request?”\n\n“The source identity is Price.”\n\n“That is the field. Who performed the submit act?”\n\nCounsel said the office had produced the accepted request object and the continuity chain presented to Kessler. Alvarez required the answer from the custodian.\n\nThe custodian reviewed the event-class declaration. “There is no matching Price PIV challenge, DIA session receipt, office local-release event, witness act, or separately authenticated Price instruction in the produced authorized range.”\n\nGrant did not let the absence become larger than the range that supported it. “That means the later request is not authenticated as Price’s act. It does not mean the office system could not inherit his identity under a continuity rule.”\n\n“Does the record identify the rule?” Alvarez asked.\n\n“It identifies a source-inheritance transaction and a continuity-construction service category. The underlying mapping and construction records are preserved but not produced under the current scope.”\n\nThe apparent answer reversed.\n\nPrice’s name had not identified the person who created the instruction. It identified the source identity and request reference the later instruction had used.\n\nKessler remained the authorizer. Drennan remained the carrier. SSO-NS-004 remained the device that traveled through WSS-4 and Hartwell. None of those facts supplied the missing submit act.\n\nJulie felt the older wound before she named it. Six years earlier, the Army had taken the surviving timestamp and made her late because the missing four seconds were easier to erase than the certified system. Now Price’s name offered the same convenience in a different form: one visible field standing in for the cause no one had authenticated.\n\n“The named requestor is not the instruction source,” she said.\n\nGrant entered the wording into her preliminary comparison.\n\nOffice counsel objected. “That is argument.”\n\n“No,” Grant said. “The source-controlled finding is narrower: the later request reused Price’s identity or request reference after his active authority ended, added operational routing absent from his original, and contains no matching authenticated Price act in the authorized event range. The constructor remains unproved.”\n\nThat sentence weakened every immediate accusation available to Julie.\n\nIt was the strongest result in the room.\n\nSterling’s public account continued on a muted monitor outside the secure intake. A lower-third banner described widening evidence of an insider network. Price’s name had not appeared publicly. Hackett wanted executive pressure applied before the office could characterize the mismatch as routine inheritance. Office counsel wanted the derivative sealed under privilege restrictions. Apex counsel, admitted only for the preservation portion, submitted a written position that automated continuity inheritance could be a lawful response to a source-integrity emergency and that no adverse inference should attach to a missing human signature.\n\nEach position contained something true enough to survive review.\n\nAlvarez asked Julie what she recommended.\n\nThe restraint held Julie’s right wrist in a position that made every heartbeat visible beneath the wrap. She could accuse Price and let the public story acquire a second convenient saboteur. She could name Kessler because Kessler had authorized the exception, or Vance because Apex’s architecture could construct inherited identities, or Sterling because the request lived in his office system and served his public narrative.\n\nShe could not authenticate any of those acts.\n\n“Preserve Price’s complete original and statement,” Julie said. “Including the expedited-retention flag and the rejected access attempt.”\n\nHackett looked at her. “Those facts help anyone trying to call him the original insider.”\n\n“They are his facts.”\n\n“They are also a distraction.”\n\n“Then the comparison will show what they are. We do not edit him into innocence because his name was borrowed.”\n\nPrice had agency in the record. He had pressed an authority boundary and attempted access after a security warning. He had also not created the later operational route. Protecting the second fact did not erase the first.\n\nAlvarez did not adopt the recommendation immediately. She asked Grant whether preserving the full Price statement would contaminate the comparison with personnel material outside the inquiry. Grant answered that the statement could remain a separately sealed attachment, produced only to establish authenticity, scope, and the completeness of Price’s voluntary account. His disciplinary exposure would not become evidence of the later request. It would remain part of the record explaining why his statement had not been edited into advocacy.\n\nHackett argued for a public correction limited to the fact that the named DIA requestor had denied the operational instruction. Julie rejected that too. A denial was testimony, not the comparison. Released alone, it would turn Price into either a hero or a liar before the source records could survive attack.\n\n“We keep him in the record,” Julie said. “We do not put him in front of it.”\n\nJulie continued. “No public release. No signer operation. No accusation against Price, Kessler, Drennan, Vance, or Sterling from this comparison. Preserve the construction path.”\n\n“What categories?” Alvarez asked.\n\n“Continuity-broker transactions. Identity mapping. Request construction. Source inheritance. Any parser or service that transformed DIA-SAR-PRICE-01 into SO-NS-REQ-6540. The authority that invoked it. The local release event. Every clock statement and event class needed to distinguish a service action from a human one.”\n\nChen’s existing Apex preservation index could identify whether Apex held matching categories. It could not provide their contents or make Apex’s record the office record. Alvarez issued separate demands to the Sterling office, DIA, Apex, and the continuity-service custodian identified by the office index. She required each recipient to preserve originals, mappings, construction logs, authority bindings, release events, and deletion or retention schedules without transferring unrelated protected material.\n\nThe receipts arrived under different authorities and different clocks.\n\nThe office acknowledged preservation of SO-NS-REQ-6540, its identity-mapping and source-inheritance records, and its continuity-construction events.\n\nDIA acknowledged continuing custody of DIA-SAR-PRICE-01 and DIA-AR-PRICE-01.\n\nApex acknowledged preservation demand categories against APX-B3-IR-5521 without producing Price’s source record or underlying content.\n\nLegislative Secure Services confirmed that SSO-NS-004 remained closed, unused, and stationary under Martin Vann, Marisol Vega, pouch LSS-P-44091, and seal LSS-SL-90418.\n\nOrtiz and Park confirmed that MPD-901441 through MPD-901447 remained sealed, separate, offline, stationary, and inside the same locked chest. Nothing in the comparison had touched them.\n\nGrant completed DCIS-CD-187463-PRICE-01 at 12:14:37. The derivative identified the office and DIA source originals, the creators of each produced component, creation times, clock bases, produced and withheld fields, integrity methods, custody states, and proof ceilings. Her signed finding occupied six lines.\n\nPRICE ORIGINAL: AUTHENTICATED / RAW-SOURCE AND SOURCE-INTEGRITY REVIEW ONLY\nPRICE ACTIVE AUTHORITY: ENDED BEFORE LATER OFFICE REQUEST\nLATER REQUEST: PRICE IDENTITY / REQUEST REFERENCE INHERITED\nOPERATIONAL ROUTING: ADDED AFTER ORIGINAL\nMATCHING AUTHENTICATED PRICE ACT: NOT ESTABLISHED IN AUTHORIZED EVENT RANGE\nREQUEST CONSTRUCTOR: UNPROVED\n\nAlvarez accepted the derivative into incident 187463 without merging it with any original. The office and DIA source records remained where they had been created. Price remained in administrative review. No immunity, charge, exoneration, or privilege ruling followed.\n\nJulie read the finding from the observation alcove.\n\nElias’s original deployment record had named him without the physical token act required to make the name his. Price’s later continuity request had named him after his authority ended and carried none of the authenticated acts present in his real request. One false identity sat near the beginning of the present operation. The other had opened the path that moved the signer through Washington.\n\nBetween them stood the successful remote Argus reconstruction, still without an authenticated author.\n\nThe records did not prove one constructor.\n\nThey proved the same kind of question had survived twice.\n\nAt 12:18:04 EDT / 21:48:04 IST, Alvarez sealed the comparison finding and the four preservation receipts under separate source references. Sterling’s account remained dominant outside the intake. Julie remained restrained beneath the camera, her right hand unusable and empty.\n\nThe next proof question was no longer whether Leland Price had issued the continuity request.\n\nIt was who constructed and submitted the `NSB-EMERGENCY` continuity request after Price’s authority ended—and whether that construction path connected the false identity placed on Elias’s original deployment to the successful remote Argus reconstruction.\n\n---\n\n12:18:04 EDT / 21:48:04 IST\n\n# Chapter 22 - The Release Record\n\nSecure MPD Evidence Intake\nWashington, D.C.\n\nThe first answer to Julie’s question arrived with the event order removed.\n\nApex called it a preservation response.\n\nThe document opened in Grant’s window under the identifier already attached to Building Three’s preserved categories, `APX-B3-IR-5521`. It confirmed that identity-mapping records, remote-product records, executive release records, camera segments, access events, and command traffic remained held. Beneath the list, a corporate summary reduced them to one sentence.\n\n`REMOTE RECONSTRUCTION EXECUTED AFTER FAILURE OF LOCAL FIELD AUTHORIZATION UNDER CONTINUITY RESPONSE AUTHORITY.`\n\nNo request object appeared before the reconstruction. No local conflict appeared before the release. No person appeared at all.\n\nJulie remained in the camera-covered alcove with her left wrist fixed to the front restraint. Her right forearm lay inside the padded brace, the swollen hand open because it could not close. Through the reinforced glass, Ortiz stood beside the locked common chest. Park occupied the witness position. Seven green package states remained in the same order they had held at the end of Chapter 21.\n\nGrant read the source list, then the summary. “Apex acknowledges every category we demanded and produces none of the source events.”\n\nApex counsel answered through the recorded channel. “The summary is the company’s responsive account. The underlying materials include privileged communications, classified methods, proprietary controls, and personnel records outside DCIS authority.”\n\nAlvarez sat in the center authenticated window. Hackett appeared beside her from the military program office. A second government window carried the Argus Configuration Control Office, identified as custodian of the product registry but not yet authorized to expose its event range.\n\nJulie kept her eyes on the Apex sentence. “That is not the release record.”\n\nCounsel said, “It states the relevant operational sequence.”\n\n“It states the conclusion without the sequence.”\n\nThe pressure of the restraint had turned the skin beneath Julie’s left cuff white. She shifted the forearm far enough to restore circulation and no farther. Park watched the movement without approaching.\n\nGrant enlarged the category index. The executive-release line carried an original identifier that had not appeared in the summary.\n\n`APX-B3-RR-0754`\n\n`RETENTION: SOURCE-NATIVE / COMPLETE EVENT RANGE`\n\n`LOCAL OPERATOR STATE: PRESERVED`\n\nThe last field changed the room.\n\nHackett leaned toward his camera. “Then produce it.”\n\n“Not yet,” Julie said.\n\nHis attention moved to her.\n\n“First separate what constructed the identity from what released the product,” she continued. “If we begin with the executive record, every earlier field will be pulled toward the person standing at the release console.”\n\n“That may be the person we are looking for.”\n\n“It may be the person who released the later reconstruction. That is the question the record can answer.”\n\nAlvarez looked toward Grant. “Two production tracks.”\n\nGrant understood before Julie finished. “Construction and release.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe Argus custodian’s window activated. A woman identified only by duty title—Government Product Registry Custodian—read the scope she could support. The registry held the prior actionable product, the failed-local-authentication receipt received from K-17, the remote reconstruction object, the release acceptance, and the superseding product delivered to allied systems. It did not hold Apex’s human operator record. It did not hold office deliberations. It did not identify who touched a field device in Kashmir.\n\nApex counsel attempted to return to the summary.\n\nAlvarez stopped him. “Preserve your objection. The release original remains where it is. No reassignment, consolidation, replacement, retention-policy action, access-role change, or derived narrative may alter the source event range.”\n\nThe counsel line went silent long enough for Julie to hear the muted television above the outer intake desk. Sterling’s image had returned beneath the same banner. The captions described an expanding insider attack and the recovery of threatened defense material.\n\nOrtiz read the chest state into the fixed camera.\n\n“`MPD-901441` through `MPD-901447`: sealed, separate, offline, stationary. Common chest locked. No movement.”\n\nPark confirmed it.\n\nNothing in front of Julie could supply the answer. That was the point. The answer had to come from people who still controlled the originals and were willing to put their names beside the limits.\n\nAt 12:25:40, Grant opened the construction track.\n\n12:25:40 EDT / 21:55:40 IST\n\nThe continuity broker’s original remained inside a Legislative Secure Services system that had carried the office exception without owning the office’s reasons for using it.\n\nMarisol Vega appeared through an authenticated LSS source window. Her camera showed only her face, a fixed wall clock, and the top edge of a sealed records console. She identified the original before exposing any event.\n\n“Source original `SO-CB-6540-01`. Legislative Secure Services continuity-broker journal for office request object `SO-NS-REQ-6540`. Current custodian: LSS compromise-control records under my deputy authority. Authorized event range begins with receipt of the inherited request reference and ends with delivery of the routed request object. The range is complete for broker processing. It does not include office deliberations before receipt or actions after delivery.”\n\nGrant had Vega state the clock basis, the read-only production method, the camera references, and the fields withheld. Internal office text, privileged communications, unrelated request traffic, and identities outside the mapped roles remained sealed. The derivative would preserve event order, field inheritance, authority bindings, request destinations, and the broker’s own proof limit.\n\nVega advanced the original one event at a time.\n\nThe broker received Price’s authentic request reference after his active authority had ended. It inherited his name, role identifier, request number, and the raw-source/source-integrity subject line. The next event invoked a continuity map registered as `APX-ICF-4`.\n\nThe map did not carry a person’s name.\n\nIt carried rules.\n\n`SOURCE IDENTITY: INHERIT`\n\n`SUBJECT REFERENCE: INHERIT`\n\n`OPERATIONAL ROUTING: MAP FROM AUTHORITY OBJECT`\n\n`AUTHORITY-BINDING FAMILY: APX-EXEC-CONTINUITY`\n\nThe broker then added fields absent from Price’s original: WSS-4, Hartwell, K-17, Phase B, emergency routing, and an Argus reconstruction destination. The resulting object retained Price’s request reference while becoming something Price had never asked for.\n\nHackett said, “Who invoked the map?”\n\nVega exposed the next field.\n\n`CONSTRUCTOR SERVICE: LSS CONTINUITY BROKER`\n\n`CALLING HUMAN IDENTITY: NOT RECORDED IN BROKER JOURNAL`\n\nOffice counsel entered immediately. “The service performed an automated continuity function. No evidence establishes improper human intervention.”\n\n“No evidence in this source identifies the human caller,” Grant corrected. “That is not the same conclusion.”\n\nThe complete broker range contained no PIV event, biometric, live operator state, office workstation identity, or witness field capable of naming the person who invoked the workflow. Absence mattered because the range was complete for broker processing. It did not turn the service into the author.\n\nVega generated `SO-CD-187463-03`. The derivative named `SO-CB-6540-01`, LSS as current custodian, the complete event range, the LSS clock basis, every inherited and added field, the `APX-ICF-4` mapping reference, the authority-binding family, produced and withheld fields, the read-only extraction method, and the new derivative seal.\n\nIts first-page limit was blunt.\n\n`CONTINUITY BROKER IDENTIFIES CONSTRUCTION MECHANISM. HUMAN CONSTRUCTOR NOT RECORDED.`\n\nThe original did not move. Vega kept the broker journal inside LSS compromise control, and the derivative crossed only after its event count, first identifier, last identifier, and source seal matched the source console. Office counsel’s privilege objection traveled with it. So did the statement that the withheld deliberative fields might contain an instruction the broker itself could not record. The production preserved both the usable mechanism and the possibility that a different lawful process might later reach the human request behind it.\n\nJulie watched Grant place it beside Price’s DIA original and the Chapter 21 comparison. The clean request and the later object now met at a mechanism rather than a person.\n\nApex’s identity production came next.\n\n"